			</header><!-- .page-header -->
				<div class="entry-content clearfix">

		<link itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" href="http://www.breakintoprogram.co.uk/hardware/computers/zx-spectrum/screen-memory-layout">
<p>The Spectrum screen memory map is split into two sections:</p>



<ol><li>6144 bytes worth of bitmap data, starting at memory address &amp;4000</li><li>768 byte colour attribute data,&nbsp;immediately&nbsp;after the bitmap data at address &amp;5800</li></ol>



<h3>Bitmap data</h3>



<p>The bitmap data starts at address &amp;4000 and consists of 192 lines of 32 bytes. Pixels are encoded as bits; 32 x 8 gives the horizontal resolution of 256 pixels. This example is a layout of the top line of the display with the pixels set at X position 0 and 255.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="./L Break Into Program - ZX Spectrum Screen Memory Layout_files/table_screen_memory_bitmap_line.png" class="glg-a-custom-wrap"><img width="589" height="61" src="./L Break Into Program - ZX Spectrum Screen Memory Layout_files/table_screen_memory_bitmap_line.png" alt="" class="wp-image-100" srcset="http://www.breakintoprogram.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/table_screen_memory_bitmap_line.png 589w, http://www.breakintoprogram.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/table_screen_memory_bitmap_line-300x31.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 589px) 100vw, 589px"></a></figure>



<p>The display lines are not placed linearly; that is, each line is not 32 bytes beneath the one above it. To calculate the screen address of a byte, you encode the address as follows:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="./L Break Into Program - ZX Spectrum Screen Memory Layout_files/table_screen_memory_address_calculation.png" class="glg-a-custom-wrap"><img loading="lazy" width="336" height="61" src="./L Break Into Program - ZX Spectrum Screen Memory Layout_files/table_screen_memory_address_calculation.png" alt="" class="wp-image-102" srcset="http://www.breakintoprogram.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/table_screen_memory_address_calculation.png 336w, http://www.breakintoprogram.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/table_screen_memory_address_calculation-300x54.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 336px) 100vw, 336px"></a></figure>



<p>Where:</p>



<ul><li>The base address of screen memory (&amp;4000) is provided by setting bits 15 to 13 to 010.</li><li>Y0 to Y7 is the Y coordinate (in pixels)</li><li>X0 to X4 is the X coordinate (in bytes)</li></ul>



<p>Note the bit positions of Y0-Y2 and Y3-Y5 are transposed. The advantages of this is that you can quickly get to the next line within a character boundary by increasing the high byte of the address. The disadvantage is that the code to calculate the screen position or get the next line past a character boundary is quite convoluted:</p>


